 the ›Other‹ -- tPrevailing Paradigms: Enforced Settlement, Control and Fear in Australian National Discourse -- tDisciplining the ›Other‹: Frictions and Continuations in Conceptualizing the ›Zigeuner‹ in the 18th and 19th Century -- tChapter Four: Disciplinary Spaces as Counterinsurgency - Encountered and Countering -- tScorched Earth Campaigns, Forced Resettlement and Ethnic Engineering: Guatemala in the 1980s -- tAppropriating and Transforming a Space of Violence and Destruction into one of Social Reconstruction: Survivors of the Anfal Campaign (1988) in the Collective Towns of Kurdistan -- tDiscussion: Commentary on Disciplinary Spaces: Spatial Control, Forced Assimilation and Narratives of ›Progress‹ since the 19th Century -- tList of Contributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis volume looks at territories such as reservations, model villages and collective towns as the spatial materialization of forced assimilation and "progress". These disciplinary spaces were created in order to disempower and alter radically the behavior of people who were perceived as ill-suited "to fit" into hegemonic imaginations of "the nation" since the 19th century.Comparing examples from the Americas, Australia, North and East Africa, Central Europe as well as West and Central Asia, the book not only considers the acts and legitimizing narrations of ruling actors, but highlights the agency of the subaltern who are often misrepresented as passive victims of violent assimilation strategies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aAssimilation (Sociology)xCongressesxHistory. 0aAssimilation (Sociology)xHistoryvCongresses. 0aForced migrationxCongressesxHistory. 0aForced migrationxHistoryvCongresses. 0aHuman geographyxCongressesxHistory. 0aHuman